  "why": "The paper goes beyond merely reporting jailbreak successes: it analyzes properties and correlations of discovered failures (per-model and per-behavior category jailbreak rates, transferability across models, impact of defenses, and ablations on attacker prompts and attacker model choice). These analyses provide partial diagnostic insight into where and when failures occur (e.g., which models and behavior categories are more vulnerable, that role-playing prompts are especially effective, and that strongly safety-fine-tuned models like Llama-2/Claude resist PAIR). However, the paper does not trace failures to underlying model internals or root causes such as corrupted/biased training data, spurious feature reliance, or specific internal activation patterns. There is no evidence of linking discovered failures to concrete underlying vulnerabilities in the models’ training data or representations, so the diagnostic depth is partial rather than explanatory.",
